ABSTRACT

This paper presents the practical, low-risk pathway from the ST-T1024 software emulator to a physical silicon implementation. Rather than proposing a costly, high-risk "big bang" tapeout, we outline a phased approach beginning with an FPGA prototype and culminating in a custom ASIC. We demonstrate that the path to silicon is not only feasible but economically accessible, leveraging proven RISC-V cores, mature semiconductor processes, and existing development platforms. The key insight: ST-T1024's architectural simplicity—eliminating floating-point multipliers, stochastic sampling, and massive DRAM arrays—dramatically reduces the complexity, cost, and risk of silicon implementation.

The critical strategic addition: This paper does not propose a single, centralized implementation. Instead, it presents the ST-T1024 ecosystem as a self-service platform for any interested party—start-up, solo engineer, Big 4, or sovereign nation—to implement the standard independently. The repository contains complete knowledge. The path is straightforward. No spoon-feeding is required.

