3. THE THREE-PHASE PATH TO SILICON

Phase 1: FPGA Prototype

Goal: Validate the ST-T1024 architecture in hardware.

Method: Implement the ST-T1024 pipeline—Intent Harvesting, FIS Triage, FSM Scheduling, Tile Activation, Execution, and 0V Power-Down—on a Field-Programmable Gate Array (FPGA).

Why FPGA first:

Advantage Explanation
Low risk FPGAs are reconfigurable; mistakes are fixable
Fast iteration Design changes take hours, not months
Real-time validation Measure actual 680 ns AET and 3.7 µJ energy
Existing platforms RISC-V SoCs are available on FPGA

Recommended FPGA Platform:

The Sapphire High-Performance RISC-V SoC on the TJ-Series TJ375 FPGA provides a hardened 32-bit quad-core RISC-V processor with six pipeline stages, dedicated FPU, custom instruction support, and full Linux MMU. This is ideal for prototyping the ST-T1024 architecture.

Alternative: The Xilinx SP605 (Spartan-6) or ML605 (Virtex-6) development boards offer robust FPGA resources, DDR3 memory, JTAG configuration, and USB/UART communication interfaces.

Deliverable: An FPGA bitstream that implements ST-T1024, verified to meet latency, energy, and determinism targets.

---

Phase 2: Hybrid Prototype—ST-T1024 Co-processor on T1024 Platform

Goal: Demonstrate ST-T1024 in a real-world embedded system.

Method: Leverage the existing NXP T1024 processor platform—a proven 64-bit Power Architecture dual-core chip with extensive I/O capabilities.

Why the T1024 platform?

Feature Specification Relevance
Processor QorIQ T1024 dual-core Proven, certified-ready
Memory 4GB DDR3L Ample for ST-T1024 tiles
I/O PCIe, USB, 10G Ethernet Easy integration
Development Board T1024RDB Reference Design Board Ready-to-use, documented
Debug COP/JTAG headers Full hardware debugging

The Hybrid Model:

Component Role
T1024 Processor Host OS, application logic, I/O handling
FPGA Co-processor ST-T1024 deterministic inference accelerator
Interface PCIe or high-speed SerDes

Why this matters: This hybrid approach allows immediate hardware validation without waiting for a full custom ASIC. It also provides a migration path: once the FPGA design is validated, it can be hardened into a custom ASIC and integrated with the T1024 or a RISC-V host.

---

Phase 3: Custom ASIC

Goal: Manufacture a dedicated ST-T1024 chip.

Method: Follow the standard ASIC design flow: Specification → Architecture → RTL Design → Synthesis → Physical Design → Verification → Fabrication.

Target Technology: A mature, cost-effective process node.

Process Node Cost Range Typical Use Case
180nm < $50k First silicon, proof-of-concept
65nm $14k–$24k Low-cost volume production
28nm $1M+ High-performance, high-volume

Why 65nm?

· Proven: Used in successful RISC-V designs
· Cost-effective: Academic and small-batch runs are feasible
· Sufficient: ST-T1024 does not require cutting-edge density or speed
· Mature tools: Established EDA flows and foundry support

ASIC Architecture:

Block Description
RISC-V Core 32-bit, minimal extensions, dedicated for control
Ternary Engine XNOR + popcount arithmetic, no multipliers
FSM Scheduler Hardware finite state machine for AET enforcement
Tile Memory 0.7 MB SRAM for domain tiles
ROM 75% of memory, immutable "Brutal Facts"
Power Gating Instant 0V transition per tile

Design Effort: Minimal. The RISC-V core can be a standard, open-source design (e.g., NEORV32, PULPino). The Ternary Engine is combinatorially simple. The FSM is deterministic and verifiable.

